    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nSquiggly underlines (and probably other similar things) don't work inside Neovim if it's inside a tmux session (does work on neovim outside of tmux, and tmux on it's own).\r\n\r\nImage showing that it doesn't work (taken inside tmux inside neoivm)\r\nThe expected output is in \"expected behaviour\"\r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/52241860/4bca9a43-bc7a-4061-a8eb-53ea39136a28)\r\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nInstall latest neovim (0.10.0)\r\nSetup a colorscheme or plugin that includes squiggly brackets (like LSP diagnostics)\r\nOpen a tmux session with the following config:\r\n```\r\nset -g default-terminal \"xterm-256color\"\r\nset-option -as terminal-overrides \",xterm-256color:Tc\"\r\nset -as terminal-overrides ',*:Setulc=\\E[58::2::::%p1%{65536}%/%d::%p1%{256}%/%{255}%&%d::%p1%{255}%&%d%;m'\r\nset -as terminal-overrides ',*:Smulx=\\E[4::%p1%dm'\r\n```\r\nOpen neovim inside the tmux session\r\nOpen a file with some text that contains a squiggly underline (like a lua file with a LSP error)\r\nSee that squiggly brackets are not shown properly, instead a normal underline is shown, and the color inherits the text color rather than have it's own color\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nTo properly render squiggly underline with the correct color,\r\nexample of neovim outside of a tmux session (same snippet as in problem):\r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/52241860/3c550917-fe69-479f-8b93-be3db3745a47)\r\nNote the properly colored squiggly underlines\r\n\r\nI don't believe it's an issue with tmux, when running the command:\r\n`printf \"\\x1b[58:2::255:0:0m\\x1b[4:1msingle\\x1b[4:2mdouble\\x1b[4:3mcurly\\x1b[4:4mdotted\\x1b[4:5mdashed\\x1b[0m\\n\"`\r\nInside a tmux session, I get the following output:\r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/52241860/4d78dcc0-2f09-4374-bf5e-011b5b13f660)\r\nwhich shows that tmux can properly display these kind of underlines\r\n\r\nFrom a few hours of research, it might be because I am using xterm-256color (I also tried with screen-256color which seems to have the same result), I was not able to try tmux or tmux-256color because it was not recognized as an option.\r\nThis also seems to be somehow related to the way escape codes work on Microsoft, as I am using the \"Windows Terminal\"\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.10.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A-\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nopenSUSE Tumbleweed using WSL2 on windows 11\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\ntmux 3.4 (inside a WSL instance using \"Windows Terminal\" on windows)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nZypper (system package manager)",
